Name: Cresol
Classification: Not classified (m-cresol)           Not applicable (o- and p-cresol)
Rationale for classification: Not pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures: the flashing point is 626degC for m-cresol (ICSC,1999). Classified as "solid"(o- and p-cresol), according to GHS definition

Name: Sodium decylbenzenesulfonate (C10)
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance is used as laundry detergents (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment, 2006), and sodium dodecylbenzenesulphonate (C12), an analog of sodium decylbenzenesulfonate, is classified as non-flammable (ICSC, 1999).

Name: Ammonium dodecylbenzenesulphonate (C12)
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Carbon black
Classification: Not applicable(Materials of animal or vegetable origin and mineral origin)
Rationale for classification: Solid (GHS definition)

Name: (Z)-5,5,12,12-Tetrabutyl-7,10-dioxo-6,11-dioxa-5,12-distannahexadec-8-ene
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: N-methyldithiocarbamic acid
Rationale for classification: Classified as "solid" according to GHS definition. The free acid cannot be classified due to lack of data.

Name: pentaborane(9)
Hazard statement: Catches fire spontaneously if exposed to air
Rationale for classification: UNRTDG Class: 4.2 PGI

Name: Tributyl(methacryloyloxy)stannane
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: chlorophenol
Classification:
Classification not possible (o) 
Not applicable (m, p)
Rationale for classification:
No data. (o-body)
It is a solid by the definition of GHS. (m-body, p-body)

Name: Tridecylbenzenesulphonic acid (C13)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2586 Alkyl sulfonic acids (liquid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (liquid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: [1R-(1alpha,4abeta,4balpha,10aalpha)]-Tributyl[[[1,2,3,4,4a,4b,5,6,10,10a-decahydro-7-isopropyl-1,4a-dimethyl-1-phenanthryl]carbonyl]oxy]stannane
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Dodecylbenzenesulphonic acid (C12)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2586 Alkyl sulfonic acids (liquid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (liquid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Sodium undecylbenzenesulfonate (C11)
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance is used as laundry detergents (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment, 2006), and sodium dodecylbenzenesulphonate (C12), which is an analog, is classified as non-flammable (ICSC, 1999).

Name: Tetradecylbenzenesulphonic acid (C14)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2586 Alkyl sulfonic acids (liquid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (liquid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Tributyl(lauroyloxy)stannane
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Decylbenzenesulfonic acid (C10)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2586 Alkyl sulfonic acids (liquid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (liquid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: [(Phthaloylbis(oxy)]bis(tributylstannane)
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Formaldehyde
Rationale for classification: Classified as "gas" according to GHS definition (gas). The flash point of formaldehyde (gas) is 430degC (c.c.) (ICSC (2004)), not pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperature, and its solution not pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperature.

Name: Undecylbenzenesulfonic acid (C11)
Rationale for classification: Classified into Class 8 (UN#2586 Alkyl sulfonic acids (liquid) or Aryl sulfonic acids (liquid) (with not more than 5% free sulfuric acid)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Polychlorinated terphenyls
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance had previously been used as a fire-retardant (EHC 140 (1993). Classified into Class 9 (UN#3151 (Polyhalogenated Biphenyls (liquid; excluding polychlorinated biphenyls (UN#2315, liquid); those with concentrations of not more than 50mg/kg are not included in the Dangerous Goods list), or Polyhalogenated Terphenyls (liquid; those with concentrations of not more than 50mg/kg are not included in the Dangerous Goods list)) (UN Recommendation on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Ammonium undecylbenzenesulfonate (C11)
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: (E)-5,5,12,12-Tetrabutyl-7,10-dioxo-6,11-dioxa-5,12-distannahexadec-8-ene
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Tributyltin sulfamate
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Coplymer of alkyl(c=8) acrylate,methyl methacrylate and tributyltin methacrylate
Rationale for classification: No data available

Name: Dicyclopentadiene
Rationale for classification: There is information that the ignition points is 503 degC, and it can be considered that it does not ignite in room temperatures.

Name: Arsenic acid
Rationale for classification: Arsenic acid 0.5 hydrate is classified as non-flammable (HSDB (2006))

Name: Poly(oxyethylene) nonylphenyl ether
Rationale for classification: Considered non-pyrophoric when in contact with air at ordinary temperatures since the substance is used as commercial detergents (EO9.5, CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment (2004))
